06508nam a22008775i 9781400849352DE-B159720210729020517.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210729t20132005nju    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979742467  a97814008493527 a10.1515/97814008493522doi  a(DE-B1597)447851  a(OCoLC)860923233  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aN6486b.C65 2007eb 7aART0151102bisacsh04a708.1/3/0905122200aCollecting the New :bMuseums and Contemporary Art /ced. by Bruce Altshuler.  aCourse Book 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2013] 4c©2005  a1 online resource (208 p.) :b38 halftones.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tCollecting the New: A Historical Introduction -- tThe Right to Be Wrong -- tTo Have and to Hold -- t9 Minutes 45 Seconds -- tBreaking Down Categories: Print Rooms, Drawing Departments, and the Museum -- tKeeping Time: On Collecting Film and Video Art in the Museum -- tCollecting New-Media Art: Just Like Anything Else, Only Different -- tBeyond the “Authentic-Exotic”: Collecting Contemporary Asian Art in the Twenty-first Century -- tThe Unconscious Museum: Collecting Contemporary African Art without Knowing It -- tThe Accidental Tourist: American Collections of Latin American Art -- tCollecting the Art of African-Americans at the Studio Museum in Harlem: Positioning the “New” from the Perspective of the Past -- tThe Challenges of Conserving Contemporary Art -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex -- tPhotography Credits0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCollecting the New is the first book on the questions and challenges that museums face in acquiring and preserving contemporary art. Because such art has not yet withstood the test of time, it defies the traditional understanding of the art museum as an institution that collects and displays works of long-established aesthetic and historical value. By acquiring such art, museums gamble on the future. In addition, new technologies and alternative conceptions of the artwork have created special problems of conservation, while social, political, and aesthetic changes have generated new categories of works to be collected. Following Bruce Altshuler's introduction on the European and American history of museum collecting of art by living artists, the book comprises newly commissioned essays by twelve distinguished curators representing a wide range of museums. First considered are general issues including the acquisition process, and collecting by universal survey museums and museums that focus on modern and contemporary art. Following are groups of essays that address collecting in particular media, including prints and drawings, new (digital) media, and film and video; and national- and ethnic-specific collecting (contemporary art from Asia, Africa, and Latin America, and African-American art). The closing essay examines the conservation problems created by contemporary works--for example, what is to be done when deterioration is the artist's intent? The contributors are Christophe Cherix, Vishakha N. Desai, Steve Dietz, Howard N. Fox, Chrissie Iles and Henriette Huldisch, Pamela McClusky, Gabriel Pérez-Barreiro, Lowery Stokes Sims, Robert Storr, Jeffrey Weiss, and Glenn Wharton.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aArt museumsxCollection managementzUnited States. 0aArt, Moderny20th centuryxCollectors and collectingzUnited States. 0aArt, Moderny21st centuryxCollectors and collectingzUnited States. 7aART / History / Contemporary (1945-).2bisacsh1 aAltshuler, Bruce, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAltshuler, Bruce, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCherix, Christophe